{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501144"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:24:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1724"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.32,0.45,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11224"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12050"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice city clinic with a two-week history of intermittent painless haematuria. He has no other urinary symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 45 pack-year smoking history and currently smokes 10 cigarettes a day. He drinks about two glasses of wine most days. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no abnormalities. Microscopic examination of urine confirms the presence of red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound abdomen and pelvis","Transrectal ultrasound","CT urogram","Cystoscopy","Micturating cystogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with painless haematuria, which requires thorough investigation due to the high risk of underlying urological malignancy, particularly given his significant smoking history. The approach to investigating haematuria involves imaging of the upper urinary tract and direct visualisation of the lower urinary tract. The practicalities of this process will be for the general practitioner to arrange imaging studies and make an appointment for the patient to see a urologist. The reality will be that the imaging studies can be done almost immediately, whilst a specialist appointment may take several weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT urogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation in this case. It provides comprehensive imaging of the entire urinary tract with high sensitivity for detecting renal masses, urothelial tumours, urolithiasis, and other potential causes of haematuria. In a 66-year-old man with significant smoking history, the risk of urological malignancy is substantial, making CT urogram the preferred imaging modality due to its superior sensitivity compared to ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative imaging option that avoids radiation exposure. However, it has lower sensitivity for detecting small renal masses and urothelial lesions compared to CT urogram. While it might be considered in younger patients or those with contraindications to CT, this patient\u0027s age and risk factors warrant the more sensitive investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an essential component in the evaluation of haematuria and would likely be performed after initial imaging. It allows direct visualisation of the bladder and urethra and is particularly important for detecting bladder tumours. However, it does not evaluate the upper urinary tract, so it would typically follow or complement imaging rather than replace it as the first investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransrectal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to evaluate the prostate and would not be an appropriate first-line investigation for haematuria. While prostatic pathology can occasionally cause haematuria, this patient has no symptoms suggestive of prostatic disease, and other causes of haematuria need to be excluded first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicturating cystogram\u003C/strong\u003E is used to evaluate vesicoureteric reflux or urethral abnormalities and is not indicated as the initial investigation for painless haematuria in adults. It has limited value in detecting the common causes of haematuria in this age group, particularly malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing the CT urogram, this patient would likely require referral to a urologist for cystoscopy to complete the evaluation of haematuria, regardless of the CT findings. The combination of upper tract imaging and cystoscopy provides the most comprehensive assessment for patients with haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT urogram is the preferred initial investigation for painless haematuria in older adults with risk factors for urological malignancy.","Smoking is a significant risk factor for bladder cancer and increases the likelihood of malignancy in patients with haematuria.","A comprehensive evaluation of haematuria typically includes both upper tract imaging and cystoscopy."],"references":["Avellino GJ, Bose S, Wang DS. Diagnosis and Management of Hematuria. Surg Clin N Am. 2016;96:503-15. Available at: https://cbc.org.br/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/0616SCdi.pdf","Ingelfinger JR. Hematuria in Adults. N Engl J Med 2021; 385:153-63. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1604481","O\u2019Connor E, McVey A, Demkiw S, Lawrentschuk N, Murphy D. Assessment and management of haematuria in the general practice setting. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2021;50:467-71. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/july/haematuria-in-the-general-practice-setting"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97199"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1724"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97199"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:36:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:37:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"htt